1
00:00:01,044 --> 00:00:04,004
-[projector clicking]
-[music playing]

2
00:00:43,086 --> 00:00:45,175
[ambient bluesy music]

3
00:01:09,678 --> 00:01:12,115
♪

4
00:01:36,574 --> 00:01:39,142
♪

5
00:01:58,901 --> 00:02:00,946
[heart monitor beeping]

6
00:02:09,825 --> 00:02:11,870
[sustained tone]

7
00:02:30,628 --> 00:02:32,674
♪

8
00:02:46,644 --> 00:02:48,342
[song ends]

9
00:03:28,033 --> 00:03:29,383
[sighs]

10
00:03:40,394 --> 00:03:42,613
-[sighs]
-[bed clangs]

11
00:04:10,119 --> 00:04:12,077
[exhales sharply]

12
00:04:12,121 --> 00:04:13,601
[exhales]

13
00:04:49,593 --> 00:04:50,986
[whistles]

14
00:04:53,989 --> 00:04:55,338
[groans]

15
00:04:58,472 --> 00:05:01,997
<i>♪ Every morning at 7:00 </i>

16
00:05:04,652 --> 00:05:08,960
<i>♪ There were 20 tarriers</i><i>
Drilling on the rock ♪</i>

17
00:05:10,310 --> 00:05:12,442
<i>♪ ...comes along </i>

18
00:05:12,486 --> 00:05:15,271
<i>♪ And he says, "Keep still </i>

19
00:05:15,315 --> 00:05:21,321
<i>♪ And bear down heavy</i><i>
On that cast iron drill" ♪</i>

20
00:05:21,364 --> 00:05:24,193
[breathing deeply]

21
00:05:25,673 --> 00:05:28,632
<i>♪ Drill ye tarriers, drill </i>

22
00:05:28,676 --> 00:05:31,766
<i>♪ Drill ye tarriers, drill </i>

23
00:05:31,809 --> 00:05:35,030
[breathing deeply]

24
00:05:45,345 --> 00:05:46,868
[exhales sharply]

25
00:05:53,222 --> 00:05:55,790
Let me get a thing of Tofutti
and a side order of Zingers,

26
00:05:55,833 --> 00:05:57,487
preferably the blonde
colored ones, right.

27
00:05:57,531 --> 00:05:58,749
[door buzzes]

28
00:06:02,579 --> 00:06:04,842
A condemned man
should have his choice, right?

29
00:06:08,411 --> 00:06:10,195
How are you today?

30
00:06:11,719 --> 00:06:13,634
[door lock beeps]

31
00:06:13,677 --> 00:06:15,244
Did you sleep well?

32
00:06:17,855 --> 00:06:19,030
[chair thuds]

33
00:06:19,074 --> 00:06:21,381
Will you come
and sit down, please?

34
00:06:23,078 --> 00:06:24,296
Bill?

35
00:06:25,036 --> 00:06:27,735
-Have we met?
-We have. I'm Ann.

36
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:31,086
Sure are.

37
00:06:33,131 --> 00:06:36,352
What did you mean
when you said "condemned"
just now?

38
00:06:36,396 --> 00:06:38,180
Federated state policy.

39
00:06:38,223 --> 00:06:41,226
You stay with me
for the next 48 hours
'til the final injection,

40
00:06:41,270 --> 00:06:43,403
they carve me up
to suitable organ donor packets

41
00:06:43,446 --> 00:06:45,709
while you're on
your tectonic transport home.

42
00:06:50,584 --> 00:06:52,237
What am I doing here, then?

43
00:06:52,281 --> 00:06:53,413
Observation.

44
00:06:54,936 --> 00:06:56,851
-When am I released?
-When I say.

45
00:06:56,894 --> 00:06:58,679
-How 'bout now?
-No.

46
00:06:58,722 --> 00:07:00,202
-When?
-That depends.

47
00:07:00,245 --> 00:07:01,377
-On what?
-Your progress.

48
00:07:01,421 --> 00:07:03,597
[door rattles]

49
00:07:03,640 --> 00:07:04,902
[sighs]

50
00:07:04,946 --> 00:07:06,600
Towards what?
Progress towards what?

51
00:07:06,643 --> 00:07:08,123
[grunts]

52
00:07:08,906 --> 00:07:11,779
[door rattling]

53
00:07:12,562 --> 00:07:15,435
-[door rattling]
-[Bill grunting]

54
00:07:24,008 --> 00:07:26,228
-[Bill] What am I doing here?
-[Ann] What do you think
you're doing here?

55
00:07:26,271 --> 00:07:27,925
I'm asking you.

56
00:07:30,928 --> 00:07:33,409
They found you in a quarry
across the state line.

57
00:07:33,453 --> 00:07:35,237
Nah.

58
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:37,108
No, I come from the right side
of the tracks.

59
00:07:37,152 --> 00:07:39,459
No, uh, gravel pits allowed.

60
00:07:40,285 --> 00:07:42,940
Just birch groves and...

61
00:07:42,984 --> 00:07:44,638
stone walls.

62
00:07:45,639 --> 00:07:48,293
Roadside tables
in the October dusk.

63
00:07:48,337 --> 00:07:51,209
[blues guitar music]

64
00:07:59,870 --> 00:08:01,219
[laughs]
That's...

65
00:08:02,046 --> 00:08:03,918
a pretty good hologram
you got there.

66
00:08:03,961 --> 00:08:05,397
Very convincing.

67
00:08:05,441 --> 00:08:07,095
Did you get her from
my squandered memory profiler?

68
00:08:07,138 --> 00:08:08,357
'Cause that's...

69
00:08:10,141 --> 00:08:11,360
very good.

70
00:08:12,622 --> 00:08:14,537
You were found at the base
of a cliff.

71
00:08:14,581 --> 00:08:17,235
-An antique truck was nearby...
-Antique truck?

72
00:08:18,541 --> 00:08:22,458
A 1953 Ford F100?

73
00:08:22,502 --> 00:08:24,329
They found you on your back,

74
00:08:24,373 --> 00:08:26,941
hypothermic, unconscious,
internal bleeding.

75
00:08:26,984 --> 00:08:29,247
Uh, you were wearing this.

76
00:08:44,741 --> 00:08:46,047
You know...

77
00:08:47,527 --> 00:08:50,878
you could help me get out
and I could make a run for it.

78
00:08:50,921 --> 00:08:53,054
-Where would you run?
-Away.

79
00:08:54,098 --> 00:08:57,188
Well, they'd pick you up
in less than an hour.

80
00:08:59,930 --> 00:09:02,367
Navy blue knee socks
I yanked off.

81
00:09:02,411 --> 00:09:05,022
She looked like
a young Jacqueline Bisset,

82
00:09:05,066 --> 00:09:07,677
and right as I went in,
I thought...

83
00:09:07,721 --> 00:09:09,461
"What is she doing with me?"

84
00:09:13,509 --> 00:09:15,990
What are you doing with me?

85
00:09:16,033 --> 00:09:17,513
What are you writing?

86
00:09:17,557 --> 00:09:19,167
[tense harmonica note]

87
00:09:19,210 --> 00:09:20,472
A few notes.

88
00:09:20,516 --> 00:09:21,996
Are you a student?

89
00:09:22,039 --> 00:09:23,127
No.

90
00:09:24,651 --> 00:09:28,132
-Wow.
[exhales, sucks in breath]
-[blues harmonica music]

91
00:09:28,176 --> 00:09:29,438
Wow.

92
00:09:30,613 --> 00:09:32,397
You got some drugs in me.
I...

93
00:09:33,921 --> 00:09:36,576
All right. Okay.

94
00:09:36,619 --> 00:09:39,230
Right, so now, tell me again,
how are we gonna pull this off?

95
00:09:39,274 --> 00:09:42,364
-Excuse me?
-Getting me out
before the final.

96
00:09:42,407 --> 00:09:44,496
-The final...?
-Injection.

97
00:09:44,540 --> 00:09:46,324
I heard them talking
at the lab.

98
00:09:46,368 --> 00:09:47,717
Where?

99
00:09:47,761 --> 00:09:49,197
They thought I was out,
in my room, at the lab,

100
00:09:49,240 --> 00:09:50,851
at the defrostotorium
in Essex...

101
00:09:50,894 --> 00:09:53,114
What do you call it?
The outer sector?

102
00:09:53,157 --> 00:09:56,378
I know all about this.
Laser border 555,
it's right past that.

103
00:09:56,421 --> 00:09:58,336
You guys had to move inland
100 years ago.

104
00:09:58,380 --> 00:10:00,730
The tectonic plate shifts,
the tsunami moved the beach in
a few miles.

105
00:10:00,774 --> 00:10:04,255
I can smell the salt on the air
when the wind's just right,

106
00:10:04,299 --> 00:10:06,257
so there's no use lying to me
about this stuff.

107
00:10:06,301 --> 00:10:08,608
Do you remember waking up
in the hospital?

108
00:10:11,611 --> 00:10:13,308
They were trying
to run some tests.

109
00:10:13,351 --> 00:10:16,267
They went to cut your hair
and you resisted.

110
00:10:16,311 --> 00:10:17,617
You were there.

111
00:10:18,487 --> 00:10:20,097
Can you remember that?

112
00:10:20,141 --> 00:10:22,143
If I say I do,
is that progress?

113
00:10:23,274 --> 00:10:24,493
Yes.

114
00:10:25,755 --> 00:10:27,496
Yeah, my regular stylist
was out of town.

115
00:10:27,539 --> 00:10:30,586
I thought they went
a little tight here
on the sides, but...

116
00:10:30,630 --> 00:10:32,022
what are you gonna do?

117
00:10:34,155 --> 00:10:35,635
[inhales sharply]

118
00:10:36,810 --> 00:10:38,202
[exhales]

119
00:10:42,685 --> 00:10:44,687
Can you tell me
what month it is?

120
00:10:45,645 --> 00:10:48,517
I don't want anybody else using
these eyes after I'm gone.

121
00:10:50,214 --> 00:10:51,651
How 'bout the year?

122
00:10:52,956 --> 00:10:54,915
Is this for credit?

123
00:10:54,958 --> 00:10:56,830
If you had to guess?

124
00:11:00,181 --> 00:11:04,925
Well, they froze me in '99.
1999.

125
00:11:04,968 --> 00:11:07,014
Cryogenics,
need-to-know basis.

126
00:11:07,057 --> 00:11:09,190
Government said they were
gonna freeze the first joint

127
00:11:09,233 --> 00:11:11,453
of my ring finger
on my left hand,

128
00:11:11,496 --> 00:11:13,760
tissue regeneration research.

129
00:11:13,803 --> 00:11:15,675
That was 400 years ago, right?

130
00:11:16,676 --> 00:11:18,678
Plus or minus, right?

131
00:11:18,721 --> 00:11:21,071
Anyways, do not do things
the government recommends.

132
00:11:21,115 --> 00:11:25,162
They just froze me solid
and left me for you guys
to thaw out, right?

133
00:11:25,206 --> 00:11:27,382
I was a decent axe man, too.

134
00:11:28,688 --> 00:11:31,691
Not trees.
The guitar, electric.

135
00:11:32,735 --> 00:11:34,345
I mean,
I wasn't that great, but...

136
00:11:34,389 --> 00:11:36,260
This was your profession?

137
00:11:37,044 --> 00:11:39,002
What are you drinking?

138
00:11:39,046 --> 00:11:40,525
Kahlúa and cream.

139
00:11:40,569 --> 00:11:42,005
Cuba libre?

140
00:11:42,049 --> 00:11:44,007
Let me get this one.

141
00:11:44,051 --> 00:11:48,011
Can you tell me exactly
when this freezing took place?

142
00:11:48,055 --> 00:11:49,709
Week before Halloween.

143
00:11:50,622 --> 00:11:53,016
-Kind of appropriate,
don't you think?
-[water runs]

144
00:11:53,060 --> 00:11:54,191
And where was this?

145
00:11:54,235 --> 00:11:56,150
Her mother was Spanish
and dying

146
00:11:56,193 --> 00:11:57,586
up in the Bay Area...

147
00:11:58,587 --> 00:12:01,024
and you were gonna marry
some governor's son.

148
00:12:01,068 --> 00:12:02,025
[soft bluesy music]

149
00:12:02,069 --> 00:12:03,853
<i>Brown eyes.</i>

150
00:12:03,897 --> 00:12:05,681
<i>We had that rare thing...</i>

151
00:12:05,725 --> 00:12:09,076
friendship between a man
and a woman, a true one.

152
00:12:12,296 --> 00:12:14,081
Don't write that down.

153
00:12:14,124 --> 00:12:16,300
-I didn't.
-Yeah, you did.

154
00:12:17,693 --> 00:12:19,260
Say, "I give you my word."

155
00:12:20,783 --> 00:12:22,742
I give you my word.

156
00:12:25,570 --> 00:12:28,791
Now, let's go back.
One week before Halloween?

157
00:12:28,835 --> 00:12:31,620
Are you going
to stay with me now
right up until the final?

158
00:12:33,317 --> 00:12:35,102
What do you mean?

159
00:12:35,145 --> 00:12:37,539
You do any
of the actual carving yourself?

160
00:12:37,582 --> 00:12:39,715
You were remanded here
for observation.

161
00:12:39,759 --> 00:12:43,066
Not to mention
erratic operation
of a blue Chevelle.

162
00:12:43,110 --> 00:12:46,069
396 and mags, glass packs,

163
00:12:46,113 --> 00:12:47,854
tuned exhaust,

164
00:12:47,897 --> 00:12:49,594
air shocks.

165
00:12:51,466 --> 00:12:53,773
[blues electric guitar solo
fades in]

166
00:12:53,816 --> 00:12:55,339
Brayberry Road.

167
00:12:55,383 --> 00:12:58,299
♪

168
00:12:58,342 --> 00:13:01,606
Doing 90, just to get breakfast

169
00:13:01,650 --> 00:13:03,391
and make it back
for first period.

170
00:13:03,434 --> 00:13:06,002
Aah-ooh!

171
00:13:06,046 --> 00:13:07,047
Aah!

172
00:13:07,090 --> 00:13:08,613
-Bill?
-[chuckles] God.

173
00:13:08,657 --> 00:13:11,268
Bill? Where are you?

174
00:13:14,315 --> 00:13:17,100
I'm tracking deer
in the Catskills.

175
00:13:17,144 --> 00:13:20,147
Or Cats in Fishkill.

176
00:13:21,191 --> 00:13:23,585
Or maybe I'm going for trout
on Beaverkill.

177
00:13:23,628 --> 00:13:25,108
[blues harmonica music]

178
00:13:25,152 --> 00:13:26,501
What's wrong?

179
00:13:27,850 --> 00:13:29,721
-Where are you going?
-Over here.

180
00:13:29,765 --> 00:13:31,027
All right.

181
00:13:31,680 --> 00:13:32,899
Pretty good, huh?

182
00:13:32,942 --> 00:13:34,683
[blues harmonica plays]

183
00:13:34,726 --> 00:13:36,076
Getting a little loud, though,
isn't it?

184
00:13:36,119 --> 00:13:37,338
Do you want to go
someplace else?

185
00:13:37,381 --> 00:13:39,819
Shall I page the orderlies,
Bill?

186
00:13:39,862 --> 00:13:41,298
♪

187
00:13:41,342 --> 00:13:42,778
You want another drink?
Let me get this.

188
00:13:42,822 --> 00:13:44,388
Bill, shall I page
the orderlies?

189
00:13:45,650 --> 00:13:46,913
Whatever you think is best.

190
00:13:46,956 --> 00:13:48,305
It's up to you.

191
00:13:48,349 --> 00:13:51,308
No, it's up to you, Ann.

192
00:13:53,484 --> 00:13:55,008
I would stand clear
of the door.

193
00:13:55,051 --> 00:13:56,748
-Why's that?
-[door buzzes]

194
00:13:57,314 --> 00:13:58,707
[grunts]
Hey!

195
00:14:02,798 --> 00:14:04,191
I'll see you later, Bill.

196
00:14:04,234 --> 00:14:08,282
Okay. If I'm not here,
I'll be down at the pool.

197
00:14:08,325 --> 00:14:09,457
Probably.

198
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:11,198
[quiet acoustic guitar music]

199
00:14:11,241 --> 00:14:13,983
You guys are pretty, uh...
in pretty good shape, huh?

200
00:14:14,027 --> 00:14:17,030
What are you curling?
A buck-75?

201
00:14:20,163 --> 00:14:21,643
[door closes]

202
00:14:21,686 --> 00:14:23,645
Thanks for dropping by.

203
00:14:23,688 --> 00:14:25,342
-[door lock beeps]
-Super guys.

204
00:14:25,386 --> 00:14:28,345
♪

205
00:14:33,611 --> 00:14:36,353
[woman] <i>
This kind of disorientation</i><i>
is what you would expect?</i>

206
00:14:36,397 --> 00:14:39,139
Yes, it's his attempt to
make sense of his environment.

207
00:14:39,182 --> 00:14:40,836
What's his short term memory
at this point?

208
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:42,882
Does he recognize you
at the top of each session?

209
00:14:42,925 --> 00:14:45,754
It's almost as if
you can see an aphasia,

210
00:14:45,797 --> 00:14:48,713
as if he's recalling,
but he can't verbalize.

211
00:14:48,757 --> 00:14:50,019
Look for it next time.

212
00:14:50,063 --> 00:14:51,847
It's important to note
if his cognition--

213
00:14:51,891 --> 00:14:54,023
-Okay, I will.
-Good. What else?

214
00:14:54,067 --> 00:14:57,113
Uh, his mood swings
are still pretty extreme.

215
00:14:58,549 --> 00:15:00,029
He's funny.

216
00:15:00,073 --> 00:15:02,205
I have to work sometimes
not to laugh.

217
00:15:02,249 --> 00:15:03,990
Share your genuine
reaction with him,

218
00:15:04,033 --> 00:15:05,774
especially
if it's appreciative.

219
00:15:05,817 --> 00:15:07,210
It'll help
with the trust issue.

220
00:15:07,254 --> 00:15:10,518
He does seem to be
locked into his past.

221
00:15:10,561 --> 00:15:12,955
-He's really clinging to it.
-He's delusional.

222
00:15:13,913 --> 00:15:15,218
These cases are tough.

223
00:15:15,262 --> 00:15:17,568
Your progress won't
necessarily be linear.

224
00:15:17,612 --> 00:15:19,353
I'm sorry you had
to call Dayton and James down.

225
00:15:19,396 --> 00:15:21,398
That's okay.
I really felt
I didn't have a choice.

226
00:15:21,442 --> 00:15:23,574
I want you to err
on the side of safety.

227
00:15:23,618 --> 00:15:25,228
-Yes, I will.
-Okay?

228
00:15:26,751 --> 00:15:28,101
[pen scratching paper]

229
00:15:36,152 --> 00:15:37,501
Well, good.

230
00:15:38,415 --> 00:15:39,851
You have a restful break,

231
00:15:39,895 --> 00:15:41,592
get something to eat.

232
00:15:41,636 --> 00:15:43,464
Let me know
how the afternoon goes.

233
00:15:45,118 --> 00:15:47,642
[sighs]
Okay, I will.

234
00:15:50,471 --> 00:15:52,952
[soft acoustic guitar music]

235
00:16:06,443 --> 00:16:07,967
[door buzzes]

236
00:16:15,975 --> 00:16:17,193
[lock beeps]

237
00:16:20,109 --> 00:16:21,502
Thank you, Dayton.

238
00:16:23,460 --> 00:16:24,809
[door buzzes]

239
00:16:26,637 --> 00:16:28,030
[Bill]
Bye!

240
00:16:29,118 --> 00:16:30,119
[lock beeps]

241
00:16:30,163 --> 00:16:31,991
You gotta rein him in.

242
00:16:32,643 --> 00:16:34,036
Can't shut the guy up.

243
00:16:36,038 --> 00:16:38,084
Could I please go now?

244
00:16:38,127 --> 00:16:40,042
No, not yet.

245
00:16:40,825 --> 00:16:42,392
How much time do I have left?

246
00:16:43,263 --> 00:16:47,963
As soon as you are no longer
a danger to yourself or others,
you may leave.

247
00:16:48,007 --> 00:16:50,096
-And who determines that?
-I do, initially.

248
00:16:50,139 --> 00:16:52,359
-And who does finally?
-My supervisor.

249
00:16:52,402 --> 00:16:54,143
-Your immediate supervisor?
-Yes.

250
00:16:54,187 --> 00:16:56,537
Okay, so you could
highly recommend to him

251
00:16:56,580 --> 00:16:59,844
that I'd be released
and he would take that
into account?

252
00:16:59,888 --> 00:17:02,021
-When you're ready.
-Well, what do I have to do
to get ready?

253
00:17:02,064 --> 00:17:05,154
You need to accept the fact
that you're going to be here
for a while.

254
00:17:06,677 --> 00:17:08,114
You're ruling out
the possibility

255
00:17:08,157 --> 00:17:09,898
of a miraculous recovery.

256
00:17:11,073 --> 00:17:13,032
It's gonna take some time.

257
00:17:13,728 --> 00:17:15,991
Well, what do I have to do?

258
00:17:16,035 --> 00:17:17,471
Let's do it.

259
00:17:17,514 --> 00:17:18,559
